Here's a minimal API endpoint that accepts multiple images plus a description field via `multipart/form-data`:

```csharp
// In Program.cs

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size (default is ~30MB)
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o => o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 50 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Read the multipart form with a 50MB limit
    var form = await request.ReadFormAsync(new FormOptions
    {
        MultipartBodyLengthLimit = 50 * 1024 * 1024
    });

    var description = form["description"].ToString();
    var files = form.Files.GetFiles("images");

    if (files.Count == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No image files provided.");

    var saved = new List<string>();

    foreach (var file in files)
    {
        // Validate content type
        if (!file.ContentType.StartsWith("image/"))
            return Results.BadRequest($"'{file.FileName}' is not an image.");

        var destPath = Path.Combine("uploads", $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}");
        Directory.CreateDirectory("uploads");

        await using var stream = File.Create(destPath);
        await file.CopyToAsync(stream);

        saved.Add(destPath);
    }

    return Results.Ok(new
    {
        Description = description,
        FileCount = saved.Count,
        Paths = saved
    });
})
.DisableAntiforgery();          // required for minimal APIs accepting form data without a token
                                 // remove this and add antiforgery if the form comes from your own UI

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **Kestrel limit** — `MaxRequestBodySize` must be raised server-wide; `FormOptions` only controls the multipart parser.
- **`DisableAntiforgery()`** — needed in .NET 8+ minimal APIs that accept forms, otherwise you get a 400. Add proper antiforgery instead if serving your own HTML.
- The client sends a `multipart/form-data` POST with field `description` and one or more files under the name `images`.

**Example `curl` to test:**

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/upload \
  -F "description=My vacation photos" \
  -F "images=@photo1.jpg" \
  -F "images=@photo2.png"
```
